         <abstract>
            <p>This article presents the findings of a June 1976 survey aimed at determining the level of sophistication used in capital budgeting by the nation's leading firms. Based upon responses to a questionnaire sent to a sample of high growth-high capital spending firms, the "state of the art" in capital budgeting is assessed in light of both available literature and comparable previous studies. The findings of the survey suggest that firms are tending to move forward in the adoption of more sophisticated tools of analysis in capital budgeting.</p>
         </abstract>
